At the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon, Republic of Korea, he became the first Chinese equestrian to win an individual medal at the Games by claiming silver in the eventing competition. (horseandhound.co.uk, 31 Oct 2015; sohu.com, 24 Oct 2014; 163.com, 12 Nov 2010; SportsDeskOnline, 29 Jul 2018)STABLESTogether with his partner Sarah Higgins, he runs Pinfold Stables in Knutsford, England. (thegaitpost.com, 28 May 2017; dailymail.co.uk, 24 Aug 2016)OTHER ACTIVITIESHe has worked as an ambassador for the Red Cross, and also supports a charity called \'Horsemanship\' in the People\'s Republic of China. "The charity is all about changing perceptions and connecting communities with equestrianism. We run programmes with as many grassroots riding schools as possible. And we connect these riding schools with children from wealthy families but also children from local communities who cannot afford lessons." (telegraph.co.uk, 19 Feb 2018; qq.com, 24 Mar 2012; alexhuatian.co.uk, 2010)FAMILY BACKGROUNDHis father is Chinese and was involved in the aviation industry, while his British mother was born into a Scottish military family. His parents moved to the United Kingdom from Hong Kong, China when he was age 10. (olympic.cn, 24 Sep 2014) '), ('Hero', 'New Zealand equestrian Mark Todd. (olympictalk.nbcsports.com, 09 Aug 2015; sports.sina.com.cn, 05 Aug 2013)In 2011 and 2012 he was named Best Male Athlete at the China Central Television [CCTV] Sports Personality of the Year awards. (hinews.cn, 05 Feb 2013; sports.qq.com, 15 Jan 2012)'), ('Additional Information', "GeneralNATIONAL FIRSTHe became the first Chinese swimmer to win an Olympic gold medal when he placed first in the 400m freestyle at the 2012 Games in London. (nytimes.com, 28 Jul 2012)SANCTIONHe tested positive for the prohibited substance trimetazidine at the 2014 National Championships in Hangzhou, People's Republic of China. He was banned from the sport for three months by the China Anti-Doping Agency [CHINADA]. Sun claimed he had been taking medication containing trimetazidine to treat a heart condition since 2008 and was unaware it had been added to the World Anti-Doping Agency [WADA] banned list in 2014. (sports.163.com, 25 Nov 2014) "), ('Hero', 'Chinese swimmer Zhang Lin. (sports.people.com.cn, 30 Jul 2012)'), ('Relatives', "His father played basketball for Anhui Tigong, and his mother competed in volleyball for Zhejiang in the People's Republic of China. The disqualification was then overturned following an appeal, and she was reinstated into the competition along with teammates Yi Siling and Wu Liuxi. "I was very sad when I was told I was disqualified, but my teammates and coaches backed me and said they would appeal. I believed everything that I did was right, so I tried not to worry about it."
